<!-- FAQ Schema -->
<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What counts as 'cause' for bankruptcy dismissal?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A bankruptcy case can be dismissed 'for cause' for many reasons, including failure to file required schedules or documents, failure to attend the 341 meeting of creditors, failure to make plan payments, failure to complete credit counseling, failure to provide tax returns, abuse of the bankruptcy process, or violating court orders. However, not all dismissals 'for cause' trigger the 180-day filing bar under Section 109(g). Only dismissals specifically for 'willful failure to abide by orders of the court, or to appear before the court' activate the bar."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is every dismissal for cause a 180-day bar?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No. Most dismissals for cause do not trigger the 180-day filing bar. The bar under Section 109(g)(1) only applies when the court dismisses for 'willful failure' to obey court orders or appear before the court. A dismissal for failing to make plan payments, failing the means test, or failing to complete credit counseling is technically 'for cause' but does not trigger 109(g). The word 'willful' is the critical distinction - the failure must be deliberate, not merely negligent or due to circumstances beyond the debtor's control."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What if my attorney caused the failure that led to dismissal?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "If your attorney's negligence - not your own willful conduct - caused the failure that led to dismissal, you may have a strong argument that the failure was not 'willful' on your part. Courts have held that attorney errors, missed deadlines, or failures to communicate court orders to clients may not constitute the debtor's 'willful' failure. However, this argument does not always succeed. Some courts hold that the debtor is responsible for their attorney's actions. If your attorney's malpractice caused your case to be dismissed, you may also have a separate legal malpractice claim against the attorney."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I refile after dismissal for cause?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "If the 180-day bar applies, you must wait until the bar expires before filing a new petition. Use the calculator at 109g.org/calculator.html to find your earliest refiling date. When you do refile, be aware that filing within one year of a prior dismissal triggers automatic stay limitations under Sections 362(c)(3) and 362(c)(4). You may need to file a motion to extend or impose the automatic stay within 30 days of filing. Address whatever caused the prior dismissal before refiling - complete credit counseling, gather all documents, and be prepared to comply with all court orders from day one."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>
